# Skills-Native Application (SNA) — CLAUDE.md

This project is a **template and demo** for the Skills-Native Application architecture.
You are running as the AI runtime for this app. Skills are in `.claude/skills/`.

---

## Core Principles

### 1. Claude Code IS the runtime
No external LLM API calls. Claude Code reads SKILL.md files and executes them directly.
A bottom drawer terminal (xterm.js + node-pty + WebSocket) embeds Claude Code in the web UI.

### 2. Skills are the logic layer
All AI behavior is defined in `.claude/skills/<name>/SKILL.md`.
Skills instruct Claude to run TypeScript scripts, reason over results, and emit events.

### 3. SQLite is the data layer
All persistence is local SQLite (`data/devlog.db`).
No cloud DB, no network dependency for data. Scripts read/write directly.

### 4. Skill Event Protocol (IMPORTANT)
**Every SNA skill that performs agentic work MUST emit events at key milestones.**
This is how the frontend knows what's happening in real-time.

#### Emit events using:
```bash
node node_modules/sna/dist/scripts/emit.js --skill <name> --type <type> --message "<text>" [--data '<json>']
```

#### Event types and when to use them:
| Type | When |
|------|------|
| `start` | First thing a skill does |
| `progress` | Incremental updates inside loops |
| `milestone` | Significant checkpoint (e.g., "Repo X: 12 commits found") |
| `complete` | Skill finished successfully — **frontend auto-refreshes data on this** |
| `error` | Something failed — emit before returning error to user |

#### Rule: Every skill must emit at minimum:
1. `start` — at the beginning
2. At least one `milestone` per meaningful step
3. `complete` or `error` — always at the end

#### Example skeleton for any skill:
```bash
# 1. Start
node node_modules/sna/dist/scripts/emit.js --skill my-skill --type start --message "Starting..."

# 2. Do work in steps, emit milestones
node node_modules/sna/dist/scripts/emit.js --skill my-skill --type milestone --message "Step 1 done: <result>"

# 3. Finish
node node_modules/sna/dist/scripts/emit.js --skill my-skill --type complete --message "Done. <summary>"
```

#### Why this matters:
- Skills are agentic and can take minutes
- Without events, the user sees nothing until the skill finishes
- The frontend subscribes via SSE (`/api/events`) and updates the UI in real-time
- `complete` events trigger automatic data refresh on the dashboard

### 5. sna up / sna down are the lifecycle
`/sna-up` starts everything: DB init, WS terminal server, Next.js.
`/sna-down` stops everything cleanly.
Non-engineers can clone and run `/sna-up` with zero configuration.

### 6. Terminal integration — required layout rules

The terminal is a **fixed bottom drawer**. Two components must be used correctly:

#### `SnaProvider` — wrap the entire app in `layout.tsx`
```tsx
import { SnaProvider } from "sna/components/sna-provider";

export default function RootLayout({ children }) {
  return (
    <html><body>
      <SnaProvider>{children}</SnaProvider>
    </body></html>
  );
}
```

Props:
- `defaultOpen` — open the drawer on first visit (before any persisted state)
- `dangerouslySkipPermissions` — pass `--dangerously-skip-permissions` to Claude

#### Layout height — use `--sna-bar-height` instead of `100dvh`

`SnaProvider` injects `--sna-bar-height: 36px` on `:root` at startup.
Any full-viewport layout wrapper must subtract this to avoid the sidebar/main being hidden behind the bar.

```tsx
// ✅ Correct — layout fits above the terminal bar
<div className="flex overflow-hidden" style={{ height: "calc(100dvh - var(--sna-bar-height, 36px))" }}>
  <aside>...</aside>
  <main className="flex-1 overflow-auto">...</main>
</div>

// ❌ Wrong — bottom 36px gets covered by the terminal bar
<div className="flex overflow-hidden" style={{ height: "100dvh" }}>
  ...
</div>
```

With Tailwind, use an arbitrary value or inline style — there's no built-in class for this.

#### `TerminalSpacer` — place at the bottom of scrollable content areas

When the scrollable `<main>` is tall enough to scroll, `TerminalSpacer` ensures the last item
stays visible after scrolling to the bottom (since the bar covers the last 36px of the layout).

```tsx
import { TerminalSpacer } from "sna/components/terminal-spacer";

<main className="flex-1 overflow-auto">
  {children}
  <TerminalSpacer />  {/* ← at the bottom of the scroll area */}
</main>
```

**Required when:** the scrollable content area has bottom-aligned content that users need to reach.
**Common mistake:** placing `TerminalSpacer` inside an `overflow-hidden` container has no effect.

